createDateString

public void createDateString(String[] parameters)
Create a datestring with the current time and specified formating. The used Locale will be US. Default timezone is system timezone. Default no seconds will be added to the time value.

You can add or subtract different types of units to the time by appending a symbol to parameter[3] Supported values are 's' for seconds (default), 'h' for hours, 'd' for days, 'w' for weeks, 'm' for months, and 'y' for years. For example 5d will add 5 days to the current time, -5d will subract 5 days, etc.

Parameters:
parameters - array of String containing the parameters.
parameters[0] argument is always the method name,
parameters[1] is a time format allowed by java.text.SimpleDateFormat.
parameters[2] is the variable name to store the created datestring in.
parameters[3] (optional) time to add.
parameters[4] (optional, requeires parameter[3]) Timezone to use in java.util.TimeZone.getTimeZone(parameter[4]) format.
If null is used as parameters it sends the allowed parameters list to the XTTProperties.printFail(java.lang.String) method and returns.

createEpochDateString

public void createEpochDateString(String[] parameters)
Create a datestring with the time specified in epoch (seconds (if<9999999999) or miliseconds since 1.1.1970) and specified formating. The used Locale will be US. Default timezone is system timezone. Default no seconds will be added to the time value.

The units of time to add or subtract can be modified, see createDateString

Parameters:
parameters - array of String containing the parameters.
parameters[0] argument is always the method name,
parameters[1] is the time in seconds since January 1, 1970, 00:00:00 GMT.
parameters[2] is a time format allowed by java.text.SimpleDateFormat.
parameters[3] is the variable name to store the created datestring in.
parameters[4] (optional) time to add to the time value.
parameters[5] (optional, requeires parameter[3]) Timezone to use in java.util.TimeZone.getTimeZone(parameter[4]) format.
If null is used as parameters it sends the allowed parameters list to the XTTProperties.printFail(java.lang.String) method and returns.
